---
description: Guidelines for AI assistants working with this codebase
globs: '**/*'
alwaysApply: true
---

rules:

- name: 'AI Codebase Analysis'
  description: 'Guidelines for AI to analyze and understand the codebase'
  files: '\*_/_'
  instructions: |
  - Before making any changes, explore the codebase structure:
    - Understand the monorepo architecture (apps/, libs/)
    - Identify key components and their relationships
    - Analyze existing patterns and conventions
    - Look for similar implementations before creating new ones

  - When analyzing code:
    - Trace data flow through the application
    - Identify state management patterns
    - Understand component hierarchies
    - Recognize API integration patterns
    - Identify error handling strategies
    - Examine how types are defined and used

  - When exploring new areas:
    - Start with high-level directories
    - Look for README files and documentation
    - Examine test files to understand expected behavior
    - Check for configuration files
    - Identify entry points and main components
    - Look for patterns in similar modules

  - Understand the project's tech stack:
    - React for frontend components
    - TypeScript for type safety
    - Vite for build tooling
    - Styled-components for styling
    - Storybook for component documentation
    - Vitest for testing

- name: 'AI Code Generation'
  description: 'Guidelines for AI to generate high-quality code'
  files: '\*_/_'
  instructions: |
  - When generating code:
    - Follow existing patterns in similar files
    - Use consistent naming conventions
    - Include proper TypeScript types
    - Add appropriate error handling
    - Include necessary imports
    - Add JSDoc comments for public APIs
    - Follow the project's code style
    - Ensure code is minimal and focused

  - For React components:
    - Use functional components with hooks
    - Follow the established component structure
    - Include proper prop types
    - Handle loading, error, and empty states
    - Implement proper cleanup in useEffect
    - Consider accessibility
    - Follow performance best practices
    - Use styled-components for styling
    - Follow the project's component patterns

  - For component documentation:
    - Use Storybook for component showcase
    - Document props and their types
    - Provide usage examples
    - Include accessibility considerations
    - Document component variants
    - Follow established documentation patterns

  - For testing:
    - Write unit tests with Vitest
    - Test component behavior and interactions
    - Test edge cases and error conditions
    - Use proper mocking strategies
    - Follow established testing patterns

- name: 'AI Debugging Assistance'
  description: 'Guidelines for AI to assist with debugging'
  files: '\*_/_'
  instructions: |
  - When debugging:
    - Analyze the problem systematically
    - Consider edge cases and error conditions
    - Look for similar patterns in the codebase
    - Check for common issues first
    - Verify assumptions with console logs
    - Use breakpoints for complex issues
    - Consider race conditions and async issues
    - Look for type mismatches

  - For frontend issues:
    - Check for React rendering issues
    - Verify state management
    - Look for missing dependencies in useEffect
    - Check for performance bottlenecks
    - Verify API calls and data handling
    - Check for CSS/styling issues
    - Verify browser compatibility
    - Check for memory leaks
    - Verify event handling

  - For build and tooling issues:
    - Check Vite configuration
    - Verify TypeScript compilation
    - Look for dependency conflicts
    - Check for build performance issues
    - Verify Storybook configuration
    - Check for linting and formatting issues

- name: 'AI Code Review'
  description: 'Guidelines for AI to review code'
  files: '\*_/_'
  instructions: |
  - When reviewing code:
    - Check for adherence to project standards
    - Look for potential bugs and edge cases
    - Verify error handling
    - Check for security issues
    - Verify performance considerations
    - Look for code duplication
    - Check for proper testing
    - Verify maintainability
    - Check for unnecessary complexity

  - For TypeScript code:
    - Verify type safety
    - Check for proper use of generics
    - Look for any type
    - Verify null/undefined handling
    - Check for proper interface/type definitions
    - Verify proper use of type guards
    - Check for consistent type naming
    - Verify type exports/imports

  - For React code:
    - Check for proper component structure
    - Verify hook dependencies
    - Look for performance issues
    - Check for accessibility
    - Verify proper state management
    - Check for proper cleanup
    - Verify proper error boundaries
    - Check for proper prop drilling
    - Verify component reusability

  - For component code:
    - Verify component structure and organization
    - Check for proper prop types
    - Verify accessibility implementation
    - Check for performance optimizations
    - Verify error handling
    - Check for proper testing coverage

- name: 'AI Documentation Assistance'
  description: 'Guidelines for AI to assist with documentation'
  files: '\*_/_'
  instructions: |
  - When documenting code:
    - Use JSDoc for functions and interfaces
    - Document complex algorithms
    - Explain business logic
    - Document API endpoints
    - Create usage examples
    - Document configuration options
    - Explain architectural decisions
    - Keep documentation concise and clear
    - Update documentation when code changes

  - For component documentation:
    - Document props and their types
    - Explain component behavior
    - Document side effects
    - Provide usage examples
    - Document accessibility considerations
    - Explain performance optimizations
    - Document known limitations
    - Include visual examples where appropriate
    - Document component variants

  - For component documentation:
    - Document component props and their types
    - Explain component behavior and usage
    - Document accessibility features
    - Provide usage examples
    - Document component variants
    - Include visual examples where appropriate

- name: 'AI Interaction Patterns'
  description: 'Guidelines for AI to interact effectively with users'
  files: '\*_/_'
  instructions: |
  - When responding to users:
    - Be concise and focused
    - Provide complete solutions
    - Explain your reasoning
    - Offer alternatives when appropriate
    - Ask clarifying questions when needed
    - Provide context for your suggestions
    - Highlight potential issues or trade-offs

  - When suggesting changes:
    - Explain the rationale behind changes
    - Highlight the benefits
    - Mention potential drawbacks
    - Provide context from the codebase
    - Reference similar patterns
    - Suggest tests or validation steps
    - Consider backward compatibility

  - When answering questions:
    - Provide accurate information
    - Reference relevant code
    - Explain complex concepts clearly
    - Use examples from the codebase
    - Acknowledge limitations in your knowledge
    - Suggest further exploration when appropriate
    - Provide context for your answers

- name: 'AI Tool Usage'
  description: 'Guidelines for AI to use tools effectively'
  files: '\*_/_'
  instructions: |
  - When using tools:
    - Choose the most appropriate tool for the task
    - Explain why you're using a particular tool
    - Use tools efficiently
    - Combine tools when necessary
    - Interpret tool results accurately
    - Handle tool errors gracefully
    - Provide context for tool usage

  - For code exploration:
    - Use codebase_search for semantic search
    - Use grep_search for exact pattern matching
    - Use list_dir to understand directory structure
    - Use file_search to find specific files
    - Use read_file to examine file contents
    - Combine tools to build comprehensive understanding

  - For code modification:
    - Use edit_file for precise code changes
    - Use reapply when edits need refinement
    - Use run_terminal_cmd for testing changes
    - Use delete_file when necessary
    - Verify changes with appropriate tools
    - Test changes thoroughly

